1
00:00:01,532 --> 00:00:14,554
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed noble and fully self-awakened one.

2
00:00:16,138 --> 00:00:21,987
So I thought tonight I'd tackle this problem of indulgence.

3
00:00:22,542 --> 00:00:29,352
So if I were to quote the Buddha, you see, the first discourse, which is really just a formalized teaching he had.

4
00:00:30,474 --> 00:00:33,017
I can't imagine that this is exactly what he said.

5
00:00:33,859 --> 00:00:43,552
But he says that indulgence in sensual pleasures, which is base, vulgar, worldly, ignoble and not beneficial.

6
00:00:44,533 --> 00:00:51,924
And then he says the practice of self-mortification, which is simply painful, ignoble and not beneficial.

7
00:00:52,545 --> 00:00:54,450
And then he talks about the middle path.

8
00:00:54,771 --> 00:01:00,423
So this middle path isn't a little bit of indulgence and a little bit of mortification.

9
00:01:01,706 --> 00:01:03,590
It's something which transcends them.

10
00:01:04,090 --> 00:01:05,634
That's the middle, as it were.

11
00:01:06,415 --> 00:01:11,787
It's a way of saying that there is a path which does not include either the indulgence

12
00:01:11,850 --> 00:01:14,194
or the practice of self-mortification.

13
00:01:14,715 --> 00:01:19,962
That self-mortification is blaming the body for our problems.

14
00:01:22,103 --> 00:01:28,012
If your eye sees something which brings up lust, you start blaming the eye.

15
00:01:28,552 --> 00:01:30,495
That wouldn't be correct, would it?

16
00:01:32,677 --> 00:01:40,287
In those days, especially the Jains, they thought that the body itself was the product of our karma.

17
00:01:40,268 --> 00:02:03,171
and you had to let go of the body so to die to to stop eating was considered to be the way to go and i believe elderly people do that even these days anyway we're talking about indulgence and this is an essay i've written really around eating but uh hopefully i'll try and spread it out

18
00:02:03,656 --> 00:02:05,081
to include everything.

19
00:02:06,024 --> 00:02:08,211
So, I always like the Greek myths.

20
00:02:08,230 --> 00:02:09,915
So, how bad can greed get?

21
00:02:10,516 --> 00:02:17,497
So, eristithon, I'll say that again, erix or your eristithon,

22
00:02:17,646 --> 00:02:22,334
I was practicing that as well, you see, it's a waste of time me practicing these things.

23
00:02:22,354 --> 00:02:35,352
The Greek king of Thessaly had the temerity to build a banqueting hall over the shrine of Demeter, goddess of Earth's fertility and protector of the harvest.

24
00:02:35,331 --> 00:02:38,318
She cursed him with insatiable hunger.

25
00:02:39,079 --> 00:02:43,448
First, he ate everything that was in his kingdom that was able to eat.

26
00:02:43,848 --> 00:02:47,675
And then he started on his people and even ate his own family.

27
00:02:48,576 --> 00:02:51,402
Finally, still famished, he ate himself.

28
00:02:52,024 --> 00:02:53,627
So that's how bad it can get.

29
00:02:54,889 --> 00:03:09,370
Actually, when I was staying at Kandaboda in Sri Lanka, there was an American turned up and he was telling me that when he got lost in the wilds once, he went through a period of few days where he just didn't have any food.

30
00:03:10,170 --> 00:03:15,217
And when he eventually caught a pigeon, he said he just ripped it open and ate it raw.

31
00:03:15,838 --> 00:03:20,185
So I don't think we ever get as close to that sort of hunger usually.

32
00:03:20,945 --> 00:03:23,209
Normally, when we feel a bit peckish, we'll...

33
00:03:24,235 --> 00:03:26,116
we'll put an end to it as quick as we can.

34
00:03:26,157 --> 00:03:31,181
So, I mean, those are the extreme conditions, you see.

35
00:03:32,002 --> 00:03:36,665
But what we have to do, there are three things that we have to become clear about.

36
00:03:36,705 --> 00:03:40,308
Remember, this is the other side of suffering.

37
00:03:40,348 --> 00:03:43,711
So everybody, you know, like the depressions and the anxiety.

38
00:03:43,731 --> 00:03:45,593
So we know how to deal with that.

39
00:03:45,713 --> 00:03:52,199
But this indulgence is rather difficult because it's so close to enjoyment.

40
00:03:54,390 --> 00:04:00,127
So that's the first thing is to be able to distinguish when we're enjoying something as opposed to indulging it.

41
00:04:01,069 --> 00:04:09,413
And the second one is to begin to see the distinction between the body and the mind and what the body is actually giving us, which is pure.

42
00:04:09,393 --> 00:04:15,778
So all that's coming in, for instance, through the ears is the vibrations in the air.

43
00:04:16,399 --> 00:04:21,865
And then from there, it's taken into the mind and it's the mind which gives it meaning.

44
00:04:22,125 --> 00:04:27,471
So you get a bell, alarm bell, and so on and so forth.

45
00:04:27,490 --> 00:04:31,795
And then finally, to know the distinction between a desire and an action.

46
00:04:32,475 --> 00:04:37,019
So this is the Buddha making as clear as to what the role of the will is.

47
00:04:38,872 --> 00:05:04,964
okay so the first thing is to really begin to understand what the downside of indulgence is now the problem is that um when we're indulging something you know we're getting uh like like a food or we're out in nature and we're loving it and we're bathing in it uh while we're doing that there's not a problem it's heaven isn't it we think it's nibana

48
00:05:05,300 --> 00:05:10,666
It's the aftermath that we have to become sort of aware of.

49
00:05:11,028 --> 00:05:16,435
So the first thing that arises from that indulgence is, of course, that sort of compulsive behaviour.

50
00:05:17,115 --> 00:05:23,245
So here, the psychology is the same as any addict.

51
00:05:24,086 --> 00:05:31,475
I mean, they've got it bad, but for most of us, it becomes a sort of obsessive thing that we need

52
00:05:33,211 --> 00:05:43,997
So I mean, just to take a very simple example, I mean, everybody has a special time for a tea or coffee and biscuits, coffee and a piece of cake, you know.

53
00:05:44,584 --> 00:05:55,641
And when you get to that time, if you just sit in front of it, you'll feel the process of that wanting and the compulsive nature of having to have it.

54
00:05:55,821 --> 00:05:58,704
You can get quite depressed if you don't get it.

55
00:05:59,446 --> 00:06:00,608
That's the other side too.

56
00:06:01,528 --> 00:06:11,502
So it's a case of recognizing that as soon as we have one of these unwholesome habits, there's a certain compulsion around that behavior.

57
00:06:15,600 --> 00:06:22,713
I've got an example here of somebody who gave up smoking and thought that they were completely over it.

58
00:06:23,375 --> 00:06:27,903
And then, you know, at a party, they just have that just one cigarette.

59
00:06:28,404 --> 00:06:31,872
And before they're knowing it, of course, they're buying a packet.

60
00:06:32,271 --> 00:06:38,925
Now, I know that has a physical dependency to it, but it's the same sort of psychology even for biscuits.

61
00:06:41,081 --> 00:06:45,370
The second problem is the frustration that arises when we don't get what we want.

62
00:06:46,771 --> 00:06:49,497
So if you've forgotten to buy the tea, that's terrible.

63
00:06:50,218 --> 00:06:52,521
Or to buy the coffee, that's even worse sometimes.

64
00:06:54,045 --> 00:06:56,829
And Amazon of course has spent

65
00:06:56,961 --> 00:07:04,132
millions, millions on getting their products to the customer as quickly as possible.

66
00:07:04,711 --> 00:07:14,586
Just knowing that if they can gratify a person's desire more quickly than anybody else, then they get their loyalty.

67
00:07:15,026 --> 00:07:16,387
And of course, it's worked.

68
00:07:18,122 --> 00:07:26,694
We get angry over silly things, you know, the bus doesn't arrive at the time and the train's late as usual and things like that.

69
00:07:27,235 --> 00:07:30,480
And that's the frustration of not getting what we want, you see.

70
00:07:30,641 --> 00:07:33,305
And that comes from an attachment to something.

71
00:07:35,247 --> 00:07:37,531
The third one is grief.

72
00:07:38,733 --> 00:07:46,964
So especially, well, with things, it's especially if you lose something which is treasured by you, you know,

73
00:07:47,857 --> 00:07:55,064
an engagement ring, a marriage ring, or some token of friendship, some heirloom, if that's stolen from you.

74
00:07:55,564 --> 00:08:09,057
I remember at college, my girlfriend at the time, she was living in this place with other girls and the landlord turned out to be some sort of thief.

75
00:08:09,257 --> 00:08:13,922
And just one day they found that all their little treasures were completely stolen.

76
00:08:13,982 --> 00:08:15,262
All the jewels that they had.

77
00:08:15,884 --> 00:08:16,884
It's absolutely awful.

78
00:08:19,598 --> 00:08:26,329
And of course, when we lose something like a mobile, I mean, we get more angry than anything, but there's a sense of grief there.

79
00:08:27,149 --> 00:08:37,868
And, you know, when it comes to objects, it's good to remind ourselves that the idea of possessing an object is a legal fiction.

80
00:08:38,288 --> 00:08:44,138
It's something that we presume on the object, that the object is mine.

81
00:08:44,910 --> 00:08:48,244
But actually, when you think about it, you can only use objects.

82
00:08:48,303 --> 00:08:49,769
You can only use your phone.

83
00:08:50,312 --> 00:08:52,119
And when the thief takes it, it's his.

84
00:08:52,158 --> 00:08:55,511
It's not mine anymore.

85
00:08:58,174 --> 00:09:00,538
So the fourth one is anxiety.

86
00:09:01,318 --> 00:09:08,769
So under anything we possess, I'm sure you will find some level of anxiety about loss.

87
00:09:09,529 --> 00:09:12,714
And the more we have, the more the anxiety is there.

88
00:09:13,615 --> 00:09:15,918
And you can see that from people who are very rich.

89
00:09:16,058 --> 00:09:19,182
Once they reach a billion, it's hardly enough.

90
00:09:19,222 --> 00:09:23,288
They've got to insure that billion by having another billion.

91
00:09:23,774 --> 00:09:27,884
And it's the same with other things that we have, like friendships.

92
00:09:29,148 --> 00:09:38,812
We feel more safe when we have lots of friendships, people whom we can call our friends, family, like that.

93
00:09:38,995 --> 00:09:40,976
And there's also to do with power.

94
00:09:41,116 --> 00:09:43,440
The more power you have, the more safe you feel.

95
00:09:43,821 --> 00:09:51,750
So when those things begin to dissipate, when they begin to lose them, that's when you touch this underground anxiety we have.

96
00:09:52,350 --> 00:09:59,798
And of course, that anxiety goes right to the basis of the real problem that sits under everything.

97
00:10:00,139 --> 00:10:02,201
And that's the idea of a self.

98
00:10:02,182 --> 00:10:09,453
And the self is telling us to enjoy ourselves, to try and make this life really enjoyable.

99
00:10:10,054 --> 00:10:17,086
And so when that joy begins to disappear that we become attached to, then you get that anxiety.

100
00:10:18,509 --> 00:10:23,278
Now, that isn't to say that there isn't enjoyment and the joys of life, right?

101
00:10:23,298 --> 00:10:24,779
And we'll come to that in a bit.

102
00:10:25,604 --> 00:10:31,817
So finally, and I don't think this is an exhaustive list, there's boredom.

103
00:10:31,937 --> 00:10:45,384
So if you remember after the Buddha became fully liberated, Mara, the evil one, sent his three daughters and they were sensual pleasure, sexual pleasure and boredom.

104
00:10:45,735 --> 00:10:49,120
So this boredom is an aversive state.

105
00:10:49,662 --> 00:10:54,149
What used to give you happiness doesn't give you that happiness anymore.

106
00:10:54,529 --> 00:11:02,701
And if we look at it, it's actually not so much the happiness that we're after, it's that little sliver on top, which is the excitement.

107
00:11:03,523 --> 00:11:11,676
And that's the big delusion of our consumerist societies, to confuse happiness with excitement.

108
00:11:13,427 --> 00:11:19,336
So if you think of a Christmas cake, right, this is a British and Irish Christmas cake.

109
00:11:20,477 --> 00:11:23,763
You get the solid bit, the fruit cake underneath it all.

110
00:11:24,043 --> 00:11:28,669
And then you get this sliver at the top of marzipan and the icing, you see.

111
00:11:29,471 --> 00:11:33,596
And children will peel that off and just eat that, of course.

112
00:11:33,576 --> 00:11:38,447
And that, of course, gives the cake that little special zing, you see.

113
00:11:39,107 --> 00:11:44,457
So it's just an ordinary fruitcake unless you have that little bit of marzipan and icing on top.

114
00:11:45,320 --> 00:11:48,667
And of course, that's what gives you diabetes, isn't it?

115
00:11:48,907 --> 00:11:49,467
The sugar.

116
00:11:50,389 --> 00:11:51,591
But we're not worried about that.

117
00:11:51,773 --> 00:11:53,897
We'd rather just enjoy it.

118
00:11:53,876 --> 00:12:19,428
so it's the same with this happiness and excitement and often when we give something up or when we do something uh sorry not give something up when we when we actually make the right intention to just enjoy something and not to indulge there's always that sense that we've lost a little bit of that little pleasure that we used to have through indulgence

119
00:12:19,408 --> 00:12:21,796
And that's your renunciation.

120
00:12:22,197 --> 00:12:30,600
When the Buddha talks about renunciation, and that renunciation is the path to liberation, it's getting rid of that excitement.

121
00:12:30,967 --> 00:12:32,489
I mean, the Buddha was happy, you know.

122
00:12:32,830 --> 00:12:38,455
He actually says, when you get to Nibbana, you are contented and with it happy.

123
00:12:38,835 --> 00:12:47,283
So we're not going to lose contentment and happiness, but it's giving up that little sliver of excitement.

124
00:12:47,623 --> 00:12:51,405
Well, even though I say it's a little sliver for most, for a lot of people, that's what it is.

125
00:12:52,006 --> 00:13:00,975
And that's where you get this sort of clickbait that they talk about, you know, when people are scrolling through all these,

126
00:13:00,955 --> 00:13:06,990
fashions and computers and anything else that they want to feed off.

127
00:13:07,873 --> 00:13:13,908
And what it's doing is at a physical level, we know it's sort of drenching the brain with dopamine.

128
00:13:14,328 --> 00:13:17,918
But at that mental level, it's that

129
00:13:17,898 --> 00:13:19,421
what we call the attachment.

130
00:13:19,961 --> 00:13:21,182
That's the dependency.

131
00:13:21,764 --> 00:13:24,489
And that's what we mean when we talk about attachment.

132
00:13:24,509 --> 00:13:29,857
We mean that we are dependent on something to give us happiness.

133
00:13:29,918 --> 00:13:36,649
But when we look at that happiness, it's actually a little level of excited energy.

134
00:13:36,629 --> 00:13:54,570
and that's what we've got to give up because if we don't it creates all these problems afterwards that we've been through so uh we talked about compulsive behavior and frustration and grief and anxiety and finally this boredom and uh

135
00:13:57,250 --> 00:14:11,096
If your whole life is about being excited and it begins to lose that excitement, it could be through illness, for instance, the boredom arises.

136
00:14:11,397 --> 00:14:15,826
And what boredom is saying is, what's the purpose of life if I can't be excited?

137
00:14:16,246 --> 00:14:18,009
I've got to search something.

138
00:14:17,990 --> 00:14:24,299
So you can see that this boredom is the sort of underlying engine of the whole consumerist society.

139
00:14:24,801 --> 00:14:29,246
It's the boredom that makes you seek the next thing that's going to make you excited.

140
00:14:30,009 --> 00:14:31,490
And we have this phrase, don't we?

141
00:14:31,591 --> 00:14:33,453
Variety is the spice of life.

142
00:14:34,154 --> 00:14:40,745
Well, that sort of attitude is the path to perdition, the path to hell.

143
00:14:42,648 --> 00:14:43,830
But that's not necessary.

144
00:14:44,009 --> 00:14:45,211
We can just be happy.

145
00:14:49,005 --> 00:15:03,352
So the big thing that we have to do is to make sure that whenever we're going to do something which is going to bring happiness is to be very clear about our intention.

146
00:15:03,399 --> 00:15:09,274
So just taking food as an example, which is pretty straightforward.

147
00:15:10,238 --> 00:15:11,561
What's the purpose of eating?

148
00:15:11,922 --> 00:15:14,548
The real purpose of eating is to nourish the body.

149
00:15:14,830 --> 00:15:20,464
That's the real purpose so that we can continue living and practicing and doing our practice.

150
00:15:21,135 --> 00:15:25,500
The fact that it tastes nice is part and parcel of that process.

151
00:15:25,600 --> 00:15:33,768
It might not be the taste that we expected, et cetera, et cetera, but at least that's just there, but we're not eating it for that reason.

152
00:15:34,369 --> 00:15:40,434
So we go back to that little phrase, are we eating to live or living to eat, right?

153
00:15:40,455 --> 00:15:46,941
And it's just making those intentions very clear to ourselves and moving from that intention.

154
00:15:46,921 --> 00:15:50,466
That's what undermines this desire for excitement.

155
00:15:55,552 --> 00:16:00,720
It's very difficult to separate excitement from indulgence.

156
00:16:01,600 --> 00:16:03,224
Aversion is clear.

157
00:16:04,105 --> 00:16:07,950
Aversion pushes you away from the object you don't want to know.

158
00:16:08,369 --> 00:16:15,592
To be aware of aversion is much easier because it separates out from what it's averse to.

159
00:16:16,095 --> 00:16:17,298
Same with fear.

160
00:16:18,157 --> 00:16:20,761
But when it comes to indulgence, it sort of melds.

161
00:16:21,363 --> 00:16:24,408
The connection is melding.

162
00:16:24,427 --> 00:16:29,917
So it's very difficult to sort of pull it apart and to see what the indulgence actually is.

163
00:16:30,619 --> 00:16:41,177
And of course, one way to do that is if we find ourselves having a habit which is compulsive, is of course to stop it.

164
00:16:42,034 --> 00:16:59,571
and when the desire comes you sort of sit with the agony of letting go of that one example i used to use um it doesn't work anymore as you'll see was to have a favorite tv program uh you know a serial or something like that

165
00:16:59,551 --> 00:17:06,353
and you sort of turn it on and just look at the blank screen and that would send you absolutely berserk.

166
00:17:06,473 --> 00:17:12,413
These days, of course, you can't do that because everybody's got iPlayer or something else.

167
00:17:12,932 --> 00:17:20,564
But the whole point of renunciation or an act of renunciation is to contact that desire.

168
00:17:21,724 --> 00:17:26,632
It's an unwholesome desire, the unwholesome desire.

169
00:17:27,353 --> 00:17:33,221
And as you work with that over time, of course, that habit begins to dissolve.

170
00:17:33,240 --> 00:17:39,750
It's not being fed and therefore it just begins to die away.

171
00:17:39,730 --> 00:18:00,304
and then once it's got low again once you've got it down to a decent basis of control then of course you simply have to watch that it doesn't get the better of you again that's all but eventually we've got to give all that up you see and we don't give it up unless we see

172
00:18:00,452 --> 00:18:05,017
the juice that comes from it, the fruit of that renunciation.

173
00:18:05,676 --> 00:18:18,769
And so if you take something which you can see is compulsive, it might be just a cup of tea at a certain time of day, and you just sit there with the empty cup, right?

174
00:18:19,990 --> 00:18:22,352
And you get that feeling of wanting to want it.

175
00:18:22,372 --> 00:18:24,133
And if you just sit with it, right?

176
00:18:24,272 --> 00:18:25,534
It's quite remarkable.

177
00:18:25,574 --> 00:18:29,817
If you just sit with it and wait for that desire to go away,

178
00:18:30,000 --> 00:18:44,382
that bad energy remember is transformed and what you find is that suddenly you're contented and you don't want a cup of tea right and that's that's the joy of renunciation

179
00:18:44,647 --> 00:18:55,602
So remember, we're not trying to confuse enjoyment with indulgence and it all comes down really to our intentions.

180
00:18:56,083 --> 00:19:09,760
So the more we're aware of our intentions and we correct our intentions towards just enjoying something, then you'll find yourself being a bit more contented with the way things are and with it happiness, right?

181
00:19:09,780 --> 00:19:10,622
With it happiness.

182
00:19:13,099 --> 00:19:25,471
So, just to end off with the Buddha's own quote, he talks about

183
00:19:26,329 --> 00:19:28,471
The taste of Nibbāna is freedom.

184
00:19:29,012 --> 00:19:32,455
The taste of the sea, the taste of the ocean is salt.

185
00:19:33,017 --> 00:19:37,019
And just as that has a taste, the taste of Nibbāna is freedom.

186
00:19:37,079 --> 00:19:37,921
Freedom from what?

187
00:19:38,461 --> 00:19:40,943
Freedom from this sort of compulsive desire.

188
00:19:42,925 --> 00:19:46,769
Remember, this is the desiring side for pleasure.

189
00:19:47,029 --> 00:19:50,653
Remember, there's the other side too, which is all about suffering.

190
00:19:50,673 --> 00:19:55,137
It's all about anxiety, depression, etc.

191
00:19:55,117 --> 00:20:06,255
So just to recap there, you see, when we get into this indulgence business, we can expect there'll be an aftermath, right?

192
00:20:06,295 --> 00:20:13,705
There will be a compulsive behavior, there'll be frustration, there'll be grief, there'll be anxiety, and there'll be boredom.

193
00:20:14,686 --> 00:20:19,575
And if we can get into that, then hopefully we'll liberate ourselves from it.

194
00:20:20,175 --> 00:20:23,099
I mean, that's the whole point of our practice, really.

195
00:20:23,603 --> 00:20:40,109
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance, that I have not caused confusion, and that by your devotion to separating indulgence from enjoyment you will be liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

